ce:section.ce:para:
At present, two major clinical treatments for cancer are chemotherapy and radiotherapy, but both of these therapies often result in serious systemic toxicity and side effects [35–40]. By contrast, PDT has emerged as a promising new solution for cancer treatment due to its minimally invasive and specific spatiotemporal selectivity [41–46]. The photoactive photosensitizers transfer their excited state energy to the surrounding oxygen for producing ROS, which leads to the death of the cancer cells directly or indirectly by inducing the blood vessel stasis of tumor [47-51]. PDT can be divided into two types, which is supported by different processes in the photochemical reaction. After light activated photosensitizer, the energy of ground singlet state is converted to the excited singlet state, and then to an electronically excited triplet state [52-57]. One is that the excited triplet state is engaging in a hydrogen- or electron-transfer process. This is derived from excited triplet state is directly captured by biological substrate to form free radicals, that is, the interaction between excited triplet state and water or triplet oxygen (3O2) for producing hydroxyl radicals (OH

                     ) and superoxide anions (O2

                        –), respectively [58-60]. Besides, excited triplet state is involved in an energy transfer process, the surrounding 3O2 is converted into cytotoxic singlet oxygen (1O2) via direct energy transfer [61]. Therefore, the latter type mainly occurs in aerobic environment, while the former is dominant in hypoxic or anaerobic environment. Moreover, the photosensitizers only cause cytotoxicity when exposed to the certain type of light, so PDT may be a “magic bullet.” It can have the option to specifically destroy malignant tumors while maintaining a least risk of side effects [62-65]. Thus, the development of new photosensitizer and PDT may offer new opportunities for future cancer treatment.
